kernel_variant.question:
Let $n=9$.  Prove that it is impossible to arrange nine distinct straight lines in the Euclidean plane so that
\begin{itemize}
\item[\,(i)] at least eight points are points of triple concurrence, i.e. each of these points lies on exactly three of the nine lines, and
\item[\,(ii)] at least thirteen points are simple intersections, i.e. each of these points lies on exactly two of the nine lines.
\end{itemize}
